wiki_catalogs.name: Project Overview
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive content for this section focused on the egor project. Explain its purpose as a retro-style first-person shooter inspired by Wolfenstein 3D, built with React and TypeScript. Describe the core goals of providing an authentic raycasting experience with modern web technologies, including both a playable game and a visual level editor. Identify the target audience as game developers, hobbyists, and students interested in game development, rendering techniques, and full-stack web applications. Cover the dual nature of the application with its game client and editor backend, highlighting key features such as dynamic level variants, 3D raycasting, procedural textures, and local storage persistence. Include high-level architecture diagrams showing the relationship between frontend and backend components, and provide context for how the various systems integrate to create a cohesive experience.

wiki_catalogs.name: Level Variants
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the level variants system. Explain how each level (1-7) has five distinct variants that provide different layouts, enemy placements, item distributions, and decorative configurations. Document the structure of GameMap interface including walls, doors, enemies, items, and player starting positions. Provide concrete examples from actual level variant files showing how tile-based 2D maps are defined with wall types (1 = wall, 0 = empty, 2 = normal door, 3 = exit door). Describe how variant diversity enhances replayability and prevents memorization. Include guidance on creating balanced variants with appropriate difficulty progression, enemy density, and reward placement. Address common issues such as ensuring all variants are solvable and contain valid player start positions.

wiki_catalogs.name: Raycasting Engine
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the raycasting engine implementation. Thoroughly explain the DDA (Digital Differential Analysis) algorithm used for wall rendering, including step-by-step mathematical breakdown of ray traversal, distance calculation, and side detection. Document the coordinate transformation from world space to screen space, and how vertical strip heights are computed based on perpendicular distance. Include practical examples from the code showing how ray directions are calculated using camera plane vectors. Explain performance optimizations such as early loop termination and efficient boundary checking. Address common issues like fisheye distortion correction and edge cases in wall collision detection. Provide visual diagrams illustrating ray intersection with grid cells and the resulting 3D projection.

wiki_catalogs.name: Player System
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the player system component. Thoroughly explain the implementation of player movement, rotation, jumping mechanics, and state management. Document the Player interface in types.ts, including all properties like health, weapons, ammo, and position. Explain how player actions are processed in the game loop within App.tsx, including keyboard input handling for movement (WASD/arrow keys), weapon switching (1-6), and special actions like jumping (F) and opening doors (E). Detail the collision detection system that prevents movement through walls and decorative objects, including the optimized checkDecorativeObjectCollision function. Include examples of how player state is updated during gameplay, such as taking damage from enemies, collecting items, and progressing through levels. Address common issues like collision detection edge cases and provide solutions. Explain the integration between the player system and other components like the audio system for feedback sounds and the rendering system for visual effects like jumping. Provide guidance on extending the player system with new abilities or modifying existing mechanics.

wiki_catalogs.name: Game State Persistence
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for this sub-feature focused on game state persistence using localStorage. Explain the implementation of the saveGame and loadGame functions in saveLoadSystem.ts, including the serialization process using JSON.stringify/JSON.parse and the structure of the SaveGame interface. Document how the App.tsx component integrates these functions through the handleSaveGame and handleLoadGame handlers. Include examples of save triggers (manual save, level completion) and error handling for failed save operations. Address security considerations and size limitations of browser localStorage. Explain the role of SAVE_KEY_PREFIX in organizing stored data.

wiki_catalogs.name: Procedural Sound Generation
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for this sub-feature focused on procedural sound generation using the Web Audio API. Explain how the SoundSystem class generates audio programmatically without relying on external sound files. Detail the implementation of the playTone method, which uses oscillators and gain nodes to create tones with specific frequencies, durations, wave types, and volume envelopes. Document how different sound effects like weapon fire, enemy hits, and pickups are constructed using combinations of tones and timing delays. Include code examples from the actual implementation showing how playShoot, playEnemyHit, and playPickup create distinct auditory feedback. Explain the use of exponentialRampToValueAtTime for natural sound decay and how setTimeout is used to sequence multi-tone effects. Address performance considerations such as audio context management and garbage collection of audio nodes. Provide guidance on creating new procedural sounds by modifying frequency, duration, and waveform parameters.

wiki_catalogs.name: User Interface
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the Level Editor's user interface components. Explain the role and integration of each UI element: the MapCanvas for visual level editing with hover and selection feedback, the Toolbar for map size adjustments and save controls, the LevelSelector for loading existing levels, and the Legend for entity type visualization. Document how these components interact through React state and props, including event propagation from canvas clicks to entity dialogs. Include examples of responsive layout design and accessibility considerations. Describe the rendering lifecycle and performance optimizations in MapCanvas using HTML5 Canvas API. Address common UI issues such as coordinate translation between screen and map space, and provide troubleshooting guidance for rendering glitches or input handling problems.

wiki_catalogs.name: Game Engine API
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive API documentation for the game engine's public interfaces in gameEngine.ts. Document all exported functions including movePlayer, checkCollision, handleCombat, and other core gameplay functions. For each function, provide detailed parameter descriptions, return types, and usage examples from the actual codebase. Explain the GameState, Player, Enemy, and Item data models defined in types.ts, including their properties and relationships. Include examples of how to interact with the game engine from the main App component. Address common integration patterns, performance considerations when calling these functions in the game loop, and error handling strategies. Document the relationship between the game engine and other systems like rendering, audio, and save/load.

wiki_catalogs.name: Getting Started
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive content for this section focused on setting up and running the egor project. Provide step-by-step installation instructions using npm, including dependency installation and development server setup. Document both game and editor startup procedures with clear commands (npm run dev for the game, npm run editor for the level editor). Explain the dual entry points (index.html for game, editor.html for editor) and their respective development servers. Include prerequisites such as Node.js version requirements and browser compatibility. Provide troubleshooting tips for common setup issues like port conflicts and missing dependencies. Include basic usage examples showing how to navigate the game menu, start a new game, and use the editor interface. Document environment requirements and configuration needed for both development and production builds.

wiki_catalogs.name: Dynamic Selection Algorithm
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the dynamic level selection algorithm. Explain how the selectMapVariant function intelligently chooses level variants based on player history to maximize variety. Document the two-phase selection strategy: prioritizing unplayed variants first, then selecting the least recently played variant when all options have been experienced. Provide concrete code examples from mapSelectionSystem.ts showing the implementation of variant selection logic, timestamp tracking, and history filtering. Explain how the algorithm prevents immediate repetition of variants and promotes content diversity. Include performance considerations for history filtering and timestamp comparisons. Address edge cases such as invalid level indices, empty histories, and corrupted storage data, detailing the fallback mechanisms in place.

wiki_catalogs.name: Sprite Rendering
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the sprite rendering system. Explain the transformation of sprite coordinates from world space to camera space using inverse determinant matrix math. Document the depth sorting mechanism that renders sprites from furthest to closest to ensure correct visual layering. Describe the view frustum culling optimization that excludes off-screen sprites from rendering calculations. Detail the rendering order for different sprite types: decorative objects (background), enemies, items, and decorative objects (foreground). Include implementation specifics for special object types like ceiling lights (vertical offset), floor skeletons (lower positioning), and table items (relative parent positioning). Explain how color variants are applied via HSL modulation in the texture pipeline. Provide code examples showing sprite filtering by collection state and enemy death state.

wiki_catalogs.name: Enemy AI
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the enemy AI system. Thoroughly explain the implementation of enemy behavior, including pathfinding, attack patterns, and state management (alive, dying, dead). Document the Enemy interface in types.ts, including properties like health, damage, speed, and state. Explain how enemies are updated in the game loop within updateEnemies in gameEngine.ts, including the difficulty-based multiplier that affects enemy speed and damage. Detail the pathfinding algorithm that uses ray direction and collision detection to navigate toward the player while avoiding obstacles and opening doors. Describe the special behavior of different enemy types, particularly the DOG type that can spawn randomly and emit barking sounds. Explain the attack cooldown mechanism and how enemy attacks reduce player health. Include examples of how enemy state changes trigger visual and audio effects, such as playing death sounds when an enemy enters the 'dying' state. Address common issues like enemies getting stuck or failing to open doors, and provide solutions. Explain the integration between the enemy AI system and other components like the audio system for sound effects and the rendering system for animations. Provide guidance on adding new enemy types or modifying existing AI behaviors.

wiki_catalogs.name: Save Management
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for this sub-feature focused on save management functionality. Explain the implementation of getAllSaveGames and deleteSaveGame functions in saveLoadSystem.ts, including how they iterate through localStorage entries using the SAVE_KEY_PREFIX filter. Document how getAllSaveGames sorts saves by timestamp for chronological display and how deleteSaveGame removes entries safely with error handling. Describe the integration with App.tsx where these functions enable the save/load menu UI. Include examples of save listing, sorting, and deletion workflows. Address edge cases like empty save lists and concurrent save modifications.

wiki_catalogs.name: 3D Positional Audio
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the 3D positional audio system that provides spatial sound effects based on entity positions. Explain the implementation of the play3dSound method, which calculates distance and relative position between sound sources (enemies, doors, items) and the player listener. Document how the system dynamically adjusts volume based on distance from the source, using a maxDistance threshold to limit audibility. Describe the algorithm for computing Euclidean distance between source and listener coordinates and how this affects perceived loudness. Include examples from the codebase showing how enemy hit and death sounds are played with positional context. Explain how the system temporarily overrides the playTone method to apply distance-based volume scaling before restoring the original behavior. Address integration points with the game engine where positional audio is triggered, and discuss limitations of the current stereo panning approach versus true binaural audio. Provide best practices for using 3D audio with different entity types and performance implications of multiple concurrent positional sounds.

wiki_catalogs.name: Entity Management
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the entity management system in the Level Editor. Thoroughly explain how users can add, edit, and remove game entities (enemies, items, decorative objects, wall pictures, and player start position) through context menus and dialog forms. Document the implementation of the ContextMenu component that provides right-click options based on tile and entity state, and the EntityDialog that handles form input validation and submission. Explain the useSelection hook for managing active entity selection and its integration with the context menu and dialogs. Include concrete examples from the codebase showing how entity data is updated via the useMapData hook's updateMapData function. Detail the domain model for each entity type and their properties. Address common issues such as incorrect entity placement, coordinate rounding errors, and provide solutions for data consistency problems during edits.

wiki_catalogs.name: Editor Backend API
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create detailed API documentation for the RESTful endpoints in editor-server.mjs. Document the three endpoints: GET /api/levels, GET /api/levels/:filename, and POST /api/levels. For each endpoint, specify the HTTP method, URL pattern, request parameters, request body schema (for POST), response schema, success and error responses, and authentication requirements (none). Include examples of request and response payloads, particularly showing the GameMap data structure. Document the security measures in place, including path validation to prevent directory traversal. Explain the code generation process that converts JSON data to TypeScript module format. Provide client implementation guidelines using the useApiClient hook, showing how fetchLevels, loadLevel, and saveLevel functions map to the backend endpoints. Include error handling strategies and retry logic implemented in the frontend.

wiki_catalogs.name: Technology Stack
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive content for this section focused on the technology stack used in the egor project. Detail the frontend technologies including React 19 for component architecture, TypeScript for type safety, and Vite for build tooling and development server. Explain the backend technology with Node.js powering the editor server (editor-server.mjs). Cover key libraries and APIs including the HTML Canvas API for 3D rendering, Web Audio API for procedural sound generation, and localStorage for persistent data storage. Discuss the choice of modern JavaScript features enabled by the module type configuration. Include version compatibility information and rationale for technology selection. Document how these technologies work together to enable the raycasting engine, real-time rendering, and interactive editor functionality.

wiki_catalogs.name: History Tracking
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the level history tracking system. Explain how the MapHistoryEntry interface tracks level number, variant index, and timestamp for each play session. Document the implementation of loadMapHistory and saveMapHistory functions that persist history to LocalStorage with fallback to in-memory storage when unavailable. Describe the data validation process that ensures only properly structured entries are loaded and corrupted data is cleaned. Explain the FIFO (first-in, first-out) retention policy that limits history to the most recent 1000 entries. Provide examples of how recordMapPlay updates the history after each level completion. Address security considerations around LocalStorage usage, error handling for storage limits, and strategies for maintaining history integrity across browser sessions.

wiki_catalogs.name: Texture Management
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the procedural texture generation system. Explain how all textures are algorithmically generated using HTML Canvas API instead of image files, covering wall textures (brick, wood, stone), door types, enemy sprites, items, and decorative objects. Document the use of radial and linear gradients to create depth and lighting effects on sprites. Describe the color variant system that applies HSL-based hue shifting to generate different appearances from base textures, including the caching mechanism to prevent redundant computation. Detail the implementation of specific textures like the zombie's facial features, monster's horns, and ghost's layered transparency effects. Include performance considerations such as texture caching limits and memory management. Provide examples of how texture functions create visual complexity through procedural drawing commands.

wiki_catalogs.name: Combat Mechanics
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the combat mechanics system. Thoroughly explain the implementation of weapon firing, damage calculation, ammo management, and hit detection. Document the Weapon interface and WeaponType enum in types.ts, including properties like damage, fire rate, range, and ammo requirements. Explain how the fireWeapon function in gameEngine.ts calculates hits using ray direction and distance to enemies, including the dot product check to ensure enemies are in the player's line of sight. Detail the ammo system that tracks ammunition for each weapon type and handles out-of-ammo conditions. Describe the different weapon types and their characteristics as defined in weapons.ts, including the knife, pistol, machine pistol, chainsaw, assault rifle, and heavy machine gun. Include examples of how combat interactions are processed in the game loop, such as playing appropriate sound effects for shooting, enemy hits, and deaths. Address common issues like inaccurate hit detection or weapon switching bugs, and provide solutions. Explain the integration between the combat system and other components like the audio system for weapon sounds and the UI for weapon selection. Provide guidance on adding new weapons or modifying existing combat parameters.

wiki_catalogs.name: Backward Compatibility
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for this sub-feature focused on backward compatibility for save data. Explain the migration system that handles older save formats, particularly the addition of currentVariant property as demonstrated in the handleLoadGame function in App.tsx. Document the comprehensive test suite in backwardCompatibilityTests.ts that validates compatibility across different scenarios including old savegames, corrupted data, and localStorage unavailability. Describe how the system gracefully handles missing or invalid data by falling back to default values. Include examples of version migration strategies and how new features are introduced without breaking existing saves.

wiki_catalogs.name: Sound Effects Library
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the comprehensive sound effects library implemented in the SoundSystem class. Document each public method representing a distinct game sound event, including playShoot, playEnemyHit, playLevelComplete, and playDoorOpen. Explain the acoustic design choices behind each effect, such as using square waves for weapon fire, sawtooth waves for damage feedback, and sine waves for positive events like pickups. Provide a complete reference table of all sound effects, their associated waveforms, frequencies, durations, and volume levels. Include code examples demonstrating how game events in App.tsx trigger specific sound methods through the exported soundSystem singleton. Describe the sequencing techniques used for complex sounds like playGameOver, which chains multiple tones with precise timing delays. Address how sound effects are categorized by gameplay context (combat, UI, environment) and how this organization improves code maintainability. Discuss volume balancing across different sound types to ensure critical feedback remains audible.

wiki_catalogs.name: Level Creation Workflow
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the complete level creation workflow in the Level Editor. Explain the process from initializing a new level (with empty map generation and default dimensions) to saving the level file through the backend server. Document the NewLevelDialog component that captures level and variant numbers, and how it triggers the creation of a new GameMap structure with proper boundary walls and player start position. Describe the communication flow between the frontend's useApiClient hook and the editor-server.mjs backend API for saving level data to the levels/ directory. Include information about the undo/redo system implemented in useMapData.ts and how it supports non-destructive editing. Provide step-by-step examples of creating a level variant, modifying its layout, and saving it as a TypeScript module. Address common workflow issues such as file naming conflicts, server connection errors, and data serialization problems, with specific debugging strategies and error handling techniques.

wiki_catalogs.name: Data Models
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive data model documentation for all interfaces defined in types.ts. Detail each entity including Player, Enemy, Item, GameMap, GameState, and others. For each model, document all fields, their data types, constraints, and semantic meaning within the game context. Explain the relationships between entities, such as how GameMap contains arrays of enemies and items. Document the enum types including WeaponType, EnemyType, ItemType, and DecorativeObjectType with their possible values. Include examples of how these types are used in both the game and editor contexts. Address the collisionRadius property in DecorativeObject and its role in gameplay. Explain the structure of the GameState including player progression, inventory, and level tracking. Provide guidance on extending these models for new features while maintaining backward compatibility.

wiki_catalogs.name: Directory Structure
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive content for this section focused on the project's directory organization. Break down the src/ directory structure, explaining the separation between game code (App.tsx, gameEngine.ts) and editor code (editor/ directory). Detail the purpose of the levels/ directory containing 35 level variants across 7 difficulty levels. Explain the role of core utility files like raycasting.ts, textures.ts, and soundSystem.ts. Document configuration files including vite.config.ts for the game and vite.editor.config.ts for the editor. Describe the purpose of the editor-server.mjs backend for level editing. Provide a visual map of the directory hierarchy and explain the architectural reasoning behind the modular organization that separates game logic from editor functionality.

wiki_catalogs.name: MiniMap
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the MiniMap implementation. Explain how the minimap renders a top-down view of the current level layout using a dedicated canvas element. Document the synchronization between the player's real-time position in the 3D view and their representation as a blue dot on the minimap. Describe the rendering logic for different tile types: white for walls, brown for normal doors, and green for exit doors. Include details on dynamic canvas sizing based on map dimensions and the use of React useEffect for efficient re-rendering when game state changes. Explain visual design choices such as tile borders for clarity and the circular player indicator. Address performance optimizations like selective re-rendering only when player position or map state changes. Provide examples of how the component accesses game state and transforms coordinates for display.

wiki_catalogs.name: Level Progression
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Develop detailed content for the level progression system. Thoroughly explain the implementation of level completion detection, loading the next level, and variant selection. Document the GameMap interface in types.ts, including properties like tiles, enemies, items, and player start positions. Explain how the checkLevelComplete function in gameEngine.ts determines when all enemies are defeated, triggering level completion. Detail the loadNextLevel function that advances the player to the next level, including the integration with mapSelectionSystem.ts for selecting a random variant while avoiding recently played ones. Describe the level variant system that provides 5 different layouts for each of the 8 levels, enhancing replayability. Include examples of how level progression is handled in the game loop, such as displaying the level complete notification and awarding 25 HP for completing a level. Address common issues like incorrect level loading or variant selection bugs, and provide solutions. Explain the integration between the level progression system and other components like the save/load system for preserving progress and the audio system for completion sounds. Provide guidance on adding new levels or modifying the level selection algorithm.

wiki_catalogs.name: Game Engine
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive content for this section focused on the game engine implementation. Explain the core game loop architecture, state management using React hooks, and integration with rendering systems. Detail the implementation of player movement, enemy AI, combat mechanics, and level progression. Document the GameState data model and its relationship to React component state. Describe the integration between user input handling in App.tsx and game logic in gameEngine.ts. Include examples of game state transitions such as starting a new game, loading saves, and progressing through levels. Address performance considerations in the game loop and frame rate optimization techniques. Provide guidance on extending the engine with new game mechanics and balancing gameplay elements.

wiki_catalogs.name: Rendering System
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive content for this section focused on the 3D rendering engine. Explain the raycasting algorithm implementation using the DDA (Digital Differential Analysis) method for wall rendering. Detail the 3D projection mathematics and coordinate transformations that create the first-person perspective. Document the sprite rendering system for enemies, items, and decorative objects with proper depth sorting and z-buffer implementation. Describe the procedural texture generation system that creates wall, floor, and object textures algorithmically without image files. Explain the minimap implementation and its synchronization with the main view. Include optimization techniques such as view frustum culling and efficient canvas rendering patterns. Provide examples of how wall types map to different textures and how lighting effects are simulated.

wiki_catalogs.name: Level System
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive content for this section focused on the level management system. Explain the structure of level data including walls, doors, enemies, items, and decorative objects. Detail the dynamic level selection algorithm that rotates through multiple variants for each difficulty level. Document the level history tracking system that prevents immediate repetition of level variants. Describe the data structure of GameMap and its relationship to the 2D tile-based representation. Explain how level completion is determined by enemy elimination and exit door availability. Include information about level rewards (25 HP per level) and the progression system through 7 difficulty levels. Provide guidance on creating balanced level layouts and configuring level parameters.

wiki_catalogs.name: Audio System
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive content for this section focused on the audio implementation. Explain the Web Audio API integration for procedural sound generation without external audio files. Detail the implementation of different sound effects including weapon fire, enemy hits, door openings, and player actions. Describe the 3D positional audio system that adjusts sound panning and volume based on player and source positions. Document the sound system architecture as a singleton pattern with centralized audio context management. Include information about sound categories, volume controls, and performance considerations for audio processing. Provide examples of how specific game events trigger corresponding sound effects and how the system handles concurrent sounds.

wiki_catalogs.name: Save/Load System
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive content for this section focused on game state persistence. Explain the localStorage implementation for saving and loading game progress. Detail the serialization and deserialization process for complex game state objects including player data, enemy states, and level progress. Document the save management system that handles multiple save slots and naming conventions. Describe the backward compatibility system that migrates older save formats to current versions. Include error handling strategies for corrupted or missing save data. Provide examples of save game triggers (manual save, level completion) and load game workflows. Address security considerations and size limitations of browser localStorage.

wiki_catalogs.name: Level Editor
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive content for this section focused on the visual level editor. Explain the full-stack architecture with React frontend and Node.js backend. Detail the user interface components including the 2D canvas, toolbar, entity dialog, and level selector. Describe the entity management system for placing and editing enemies, items, and decorative objects. Document the level creation workflow from new level initialization to saving to the levels/ directory. Explain the communication between frontend and backend via the editor-server.mjs API. Include information about coordinate systems, grid snapping, and level dimension configuration. Provide guidance on best practices for level design and avoiding common pitfalls in level creation.

wiki_catalogs.name: API Reference
wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create API documentation for the public interfaces of the egor project. For the frontend API, document the exported functions and types in gameEngine.ts, raycasting.ts, and other core modules, including parameters, return values, and usage examples. For the editor backend API, create documentation for the RESTful endpoints in editor-server.mjs including HTTP methods, URL patterns, request/response schemas, and authentication methods (if any). Document the data models defined in types.ts with field definitions, data types, and relationships. Include client implementation guidelines for both game and editor APIs. Address versioning considerations and backward compatibility. Provide code examples showing how to interact with each API endpoint and integrate with the existing codebase.

wiki_catalogs.prompt: Create comprehensive content for this section focused on contributing to the egor project. Document the code style guidelines enforced by ESLint and TypeScript, including naming conventions, formatting rules, and best practices. Explain the pull request process from fork to merge, including branch naming conventions and review requirements. Detail the issue reporting process with templates for bugs and feature requests. Describe the testing procedures and any automated tests that should be run before submission. Include information about the React compiler plugin and other development tools. wiki_overview.content:
<blog>
# Comprehensive Project Analysis: Hundefelsen - A Wolfenstein 3D Homage

## 1. Project Introduction

### Purpose Statement
Hundefelsen is a retro-style first-person shooter game inspired by Wolfenstein 3D, built with modern web technologies. The project recreates the classic 3D raycasting engine experience while adding contemporary features and improvements.

### Core Goals and Objectives
- Implement a functional 3D raycasting engine using React and TypeScript
- Create an engaging retro gaming experience with multiple levels and enemy types
- Develop a visual level editor for creating and modifying game levels
- Optimize performance for smooth gameplay at 60 FPS
- Provide a complete game experience with sound, weapons, items, and progression

### Target Audience
- Web developers interested in game development
- Retro gaming enthusiasts
- React and TypeScript learners
- Developers interested in 3D rendering techniques
- Fans of classic first-person shooters

## 2. Technical Architecture

### Component Breakdown
The project follows a modular architecture with clear separation between game engine, rendering, state management, and UI components. The core components include:

- **Game Engine**: Handles game logic, player movement, enemy AI, and combat
- **Raycasting Engine**: Implements 3D rendering on canvas
- **State Management**: Uses React state and refs for game state
- **UI Components**: React components for menus, HUD, and editor
- **Level System**: Manages multiple level variants with dynamic selection
- **Audio System**: Web Audio API implementation for sound effects

### Design Patterns
The project employs several design patterns:

- **Singleton Pattern**: For the sound system
- **Observer Pattern**: Through React's state management
- **Factory Pattern**: For creating game entities and textures
- **State Pattern**: For enemy states (alive, dying, dead)
- **Component Pattern**: React's component-based architecture

### System Relationships
```mermaid
flowchart TD
  A[User Input] --> B[App Component]
  B --> C[Game Engine]
  C --> D[Raycasting Engine]
  D --> E[Canvas Rendering]
  C --> F[Enemy AI]
  C --> G[Collision Detection]
  C --> H[Item Collection]
  F --> I[Pathfinding]
  G --> J[Map Data]
  H --> K[Score System]
  B --> L[UI Components]
  L --> M[MiniMap]
  L --> N[Menu System]
  C --> O[Sound System]
  P[Level Data] --> C
  P --> Q[Level Editor]
```

### Data Flow
```mermaid
flowchart TD
  A[Keyboard Input] --> B[Event Listeners]
  B --> C[Game State Update]
  C --> D[Game Loop]
  D --> E[Physics Calculations]
  D --> F[Enemy AI Update]
  D --> G[Collision Detection]
  D --> H[Rendering]
  H --> I[Canvas]
  E --> J[Player Position]
  F --> K[Enemy Movement]
  G --> L[Game Logic]
  L --> M[Score/Health Updates]
  M --> C
```

## 3. Key Implementation

### Main Entry Points
- [main.tsx](src/main.tsx): Application entry point that renders the App component
- [App.tsx](src/App.tsx): Main game component that manages game state and rendering
- [editor/main.tsx](src/editor/main.tsx): Entry point for the level editor

### Core Modules
- [gameEngine.ts](src/gameEngine.ts): Core game logic and state management
- [raycasting.ts](src/raycasting.ts): 3D rendering engine implementation
- [types.ts](src/types.ts): TypeScript interfaces and enums
- [textures.ts](src/textures.ts): Procedural texture generation
- [soundSystem.ts](src/soundSystem.ts): Audio effects system

### Configuration Approach
- [vite.config.ts](vite.config.ts): Vite build configuration
- [package.json](package.json): Project dependencies and scripts
- [tsconfig.json](tsconfig.json): TypeScript configuration
- [eslint.config.js](eslint.config.js): Code linting configuration

### External Dependencies
- [package.json](package.json): Lists React, Vite, and development tools
- React 19 with TypeScript
- Vite as the build tool
- ESLint for code quality
- Concurrently for running multiple processes

### Integration Points
- [editor-server.mjs](editor-server.mjs): Backend server for the level editor
- [editor.html](editor.html): HTML entry point for the editor
- [AGENTS.md](AGENTS.md): Documentation for development agents

### Component Relationships
```mermaid
graph LR
  A[App] --> B[Game Engine]
  A --> C[Raycasting]
  A --> D[Sound System]
  A --> E[MiniMap]
  A --> F[Menu System]
  B --> G[Collision Detection]
  B --> H[Enemy AI]
  B --> I[Item System]
  C --> J[Canvas Rendering]
  G --> K[Map Data]
  H --> K
  I --> K
  B --> L[Save/Load System]
  M[Level Editor] --> K
  M --> N[Level Variants]
```

## 4. Key Features

### Functionality Overview
Hundefelsen is a complete first-person shooter game with the following key features:

- 3D raycasting engine for retro-style graphics
- 8 levels with multiple variants each
- 6 different weapons with unique characteristics
- 4 enemy types with distinct behaviors and appearances
- Dynamic level selection with automatic variant rotation
- Level completion rewards (25 HP per level)
- Door mechanics (normal doors and exit doors)
- Jumping mechanic to reach elevated items
- Decorative objects and wall pictures
- Comprehensive statistics tracking
- Local storage for saving game progress
- Visual level editor for content creation

### Implementation Highlights
- **Raycasting Engine**: Implements the Digital Differential Analysis (DDA) algorithm for efficient ray casting
- **Procedural Textures**: Generates all textures programmatically without image files
- **Web Audio API**: Creates sound effects procedurally without audio files
- **View Frustum Culling**: Optimizes rendering by only drawing visible sprites
- **Dynamic Level Selection**: Rotates through level variants to increase replayability
- **Collision Detection**: Handles both wall and decorative object collisions
- **Enemy AI**: Implements pathfinding with door interaction capabilities

```mermaid
stateDiagram-v2

    Menu --> NewGame: Start Game

    LoadGame --> GamePlaying: Select Save
    Help --> Menu: Close Help
    GamePlaying --> Paused: Press P
    GamePlaying --> GameOver: Health <= 0
    GamePlaying --> LevelComplete: All Enemies Defeated
    Paused --> GamePlaying: Resume
    LevelComplete --> GamePlaying: Continue to Next Level
    GameOver --> Menu: Return to Menu
    GamePlaying --> SaveMenu: Press M
    GamePlaying --> LoadMenu: Press L
    SaveMenu --> GamePlaying: Save Complete
    LoadMenu --> GamePlaying: Load Complete
```
